english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Works of Master Chun'jeong
  author: Gwon Je
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In ancient times, the court appointed officials to gather poems and thereby observe the customs of the people. Poetry, after all, springs forth from the heart and represents the finest distillation of words. Its power to move the human soul runs deep, and through it the rise and fall of royal virtue and the ascent and descent of the Way reveal themselves. How then could the utility of poetry ever be deemed trivial?

    Master Byeon of Chun'jeong possessed keen natural gifts and pursued learning with precision and breadth. Before reaching his twentieth year, he took as his teachers the venerable Masters Gohu and Toeu, and my own father, Duke Yangchon of the Literary Archive. The great scholars of his time praised him lavishly, and his fame spread far and wide each passing day. Thus he came to serve in the presence of the ruler, consistently entrusted with the composition of imperial edicts and decrees, most of which flowed from his brush. His prose displays classical elegance and transcendent refinement; in poetry especially he excels. His verses are clear without severity, serene without shallowness—one might say he has ascended to the hall of the great masters and stands undiminished beside the ancient poets.

    Our late King Taejong elevated him to the rank of Prime Minister, heeding his counsel and strategies, by which he rendered great service. Our present Sovereign shows him even greater favor, keeping him near in the royal study. Though possessed of a sage's innate wisdom requiring no consultation, His Majesty's profound humility in learning finds deep reliance in the Master's guidance. The Master once composed new melodies celebrating the filial devotion of the two palaces and depicting the achievements of our era, setting them to music for eternal transmission—work that surely surpasses what mere poets and literati could accomplish with their idle musings on wind and moon.

    The literary works and deeds of the Master are indeed illustrious. In his leisure from myriad duties, our Sovereign recalled his beloved teacher and lamented that the Master's manuscripts faced oblivion. He therefore commanded the Hall of Worthies to collate and verify them, and had them printed in Gyeongsang Province for wider circulation. Through such reverence for scholars, esteem for the Way, love of learning, and delight in goodness, His Majesty's virtue surpasses that of countless kings before him. What need then to speak of gathering poems and observing the people's customs?

    Ah, how sublime! I, your subject Gwon Je, having received this command from the Sovereign, dare not decline on account of my limited abilities. Thus I have set brush to paper and composed this preface.
  footnotes:
    - Gohu (圃隱) and Toeu (陶隱) were respected Neo-Confucian masters of the Goryeo-Joseon transitional period.
    - The 'two palaces' (兩宮) likely refers to the Queen Mother and the Queen, a common subject of court poetry.
    - The Hall of Worthies (集賢殿) was Joseon's premier scholarly institution, responsible for compiling and preserving important texts.
